Hello, my name is Maddie, and welcome to my endless pursuit of a creative outlet!

Not sure if I have my mom or my high school art teacher (shout out Mr. Falwell!) to credit for lighting the fire in me, but either way, it’s continued to burn in to my adulthood…To the point where now, I get to share it with a ton of people all over the world. That’s pretty fricken awesome!

I truly believe art is just as integral for mental health as exercise is for physical health (though I partake in a lot more of the former) and my mission is to make everyone feel capable of doing what I do, because, guess what? You totally are!

If something I create has inspired you to be creative, in any form, then mission accomplished!

Thanks for coming along for the ride, I hope I can continue to inspire you along the way!

📸: @emilywitt.photography.mn

There are lots of different ways to do gender reveal cookies, this is the method that works for me:

1. Cut a hole out of your cookie. Works best with chilled dough. 
2. Trim the cut-out piece of dough to half the thickness. I used a cheese slicer to do this (though the filmed part in the video didn’t work as I was doing it with one hand 😆).

3. Reattach the dough and bake. Then fill with royal icing color of choice. 

4. Wait til middle filling is dry before layering the top half of icing. 

And there you have it. Gender reveal cookies!

You don’t need custom cookies for a baby shower. Or a birthday. Or a wedding. Or any other occasion for that matter. 

Just like you don’t need a pretty cake. Floral arrangements. Fancy decorations. Charcuterie boards.

These are just things.

But they’re things that make the celebration feel a little more special, a little more recognized, a little more, well, …celebrated. 

When I was little my mom would decorate our whole house with streamers and balloons for our birthdays. She would collage pictures of us and make posters proudly displaying our new age. She would make elaborate cakes. She would cook our favorite meal. She would wrap gifts so ornately sometimes you wouldn’t even want to open them. The wrapping paper was always our favorite color. 

My point is, you don’t *need* any of these things to have a birthday. But you just might need a couple, like cookies and streamers, to make it a day they’ll never forget.

They come to me in a series of dreams and then I wake up and immediately turn my dreams in to reality.

Typically what I do is grab a cookie cutter that sparks absolutely NO immediate ideas, so I’m challenged to really examine it without any prior bias.
